1
00:02:50,796 --> 00:02:52,172
The usurper.

2
00:02:54,049 --> 00:02:56,426
<i>Caro?</i> He's here.

3
00:03:17,155 --> 00:03:19,199
- Professor Perlman.
- Welcome, welcome.

4
00:03:19,282 --> 00:03:21,368
- Thank you so much for having me.
- Oh, my goodness.

5
00:03:21,451 --> 00:03:22,911
You're bigger than your picture.

6
00:03:22,994 --> 00:03:24,496
Well, I couldn't get
all of me in the photo.

7
00:03:24,579 --> 00:03:26,331
That's the problem.

8
00:03:26,873 --> 00:03:28,333
He seems very confident.

9
00:03:29,418 --> 00:03:30,794
- Mrs. Perlman.
- Annella.

10
00:03:30,877 --> 00:03:32,254
Oliver. Very nice to meet you.

11
00:03:32,337 --> 00:03:33,755
- Thank you for having me in your home.
- Welcome.

12
00:03:33,839 --> 00:03:35,090
Where's Elio?

13
00:03:35,465 --> 00:03:36,633
I'll go down.

14
00:03:36,717 --> 00:03:37,968
Elio?

15
00:03:38,051 --> 00:03:41,263
- You must be exhausted.
- What gave me away?

16
00:03:52,899 --> 00:03:53,942
Hey.

17
00:03:54,025 --> 00:03:56,486
Darling, come help Oliver
take his things up to his room.

18
00:03:56,570 --> 00:03:57,988
- He's already here?
- Yes!

19
00:03:58,780 --> 00:04:01,241
Every single one of these will.

20
00:04:01,324 --> 00:04:03,201
Elio, Oliver. Oliver, Elio.

21
00:04:03,285 --> 00:04:05,036
- How you doing?
- Nice to meet you. Elio.

22
00:04:05,120 --> 00:04:06,830
You must be exhausted.

23
00:04:06,913 --> 00:04:09,040
- A little bit.
- Come, come, come.

24
00:04:09,124 --> 00:04:10,876
May I bring your things up to your room?

25
00:04:10,959 --> 00:04:13,044
- Sure. Yeah.
- My room?

26
00:04:15,338 --> 00:04:17,090
Follow him.

27
00:04:17,174 --> 00:04:19,384
- You're very welcome here.
<i>- Si.</i>

28
00:04:19,468 --> 00:04:21,386
Our home is your home.

29
00:04:27,601 --> 00:04:28,935
You're leaving?

30
00:04:29,019 --> 00:04:32,063
- Hello.
- Hi.

31
00:04:32,939 --> 00:04:34,024
Nice to meet you.

32
00:05:00,300 --> 00:05:02,677
My room is now your room.

33
00:05:02,761 --> 00:05:04,596
I'll be next door.

34
00:05:08,183 --> 00:05:10,894
We have to share the bathroom.

35
00:05:11,561 --> 00:05:13,104
It's my only way out.

36
00:06:03,989 --> 00:06:06,157
We're being called for dinner.

37
00:06:47,949 --> 00:06:49,743
Sorry.

38
00:06:51,244 --> 00:06:52,412
Yeah.

39
00:06:52,495 --> 00:06:54,289
We're being called for dinner.

40
00:06:54,706 --> 00:06:57,834
Yeah, I'm probably gonna pass.

41
00:06:57,918 --> 00:07:00,587
Will you make an excuse for me
to your mom, though?

42
00:07:02,589 --> 00:07:04,382
Thanks, man.

43
00:07:06,718 --> 00:07:08,720
So, this is your old room, huh?

44
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:12,474
Thanks.

45
00:07:14,517 --> 00:07:15,977
Later.

46
00:08:03,733 --> 00:08:05,443
I'll take care of the tart.

47
00:08:09,656 --> 00:08:10,991
Look at this.

48
00:08:11,074 --> 00:08:12,409
Good morning, Professor.

49
00:08:12,492 --> 00:08:13,952
- Good morning.
- Back from the dead.

50
00:08:14,035 --> 00:08:16,037
- Was I out that long?
- It seemed like it, huh?

51
00:08:16,121 --> 00:08:18,498
- How are you?
- I... Well, rested now.

52
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:20,041
- Thank you.
- I'm glad.

53
00:08:20,125 --> 00:08:21,418
Would you like some espresso?

54
00:08:21,501 --> 00:08:23,503
I would love some. Thank you very much.

55
00:08:23,586 --> 00:08:25,922
This looks amazing.
I didn't take your seat, did I?

56
00:08:26,006 --> 00:08:28,717
No, no, no. It's okay. Please.

57
00:08:28,800 --> 00:08:30,760
Did you...
Did you recover from your trip?

58
00:08:30,844 --> 00:08:32,220
I did. Yeah, big time.

59
00:08:32,303 --> 00:08:34,014
- Thank you.
- Good.

60
00:08:34,097 --> 00:08:35,682
I could show you around.

61
00:08:35,765 --> 00:08:37,392
That'd be great. Thank you.

62
00:08:37,475 --> 00:08:39,394
Is there a... Is there a bank in town?

63
00:08:39,477 --> 00:08:41,771
I'd love to start
an account while I'm here.

64
00:08:42,939 --> 00:08:44,441
Let me do it.

65
00:08:44,524 --> 00:08:45,734
Sorry.

66
00:08:46,234 --> 00:08:49,279
- It happens to the best of us.
- Yeah, well...

67
00:08:49,362 --> 00:08:52,282
None of our residents has ever
had a local bank account.

68
00:08:52,365 --> 00:08:53,825
Really?

69
00:08:53,908 --> 00:08:55,702
Should I take him to Montodine?

70
00:08:55,785 --> 00:08:57,996
I think they're closed
for summer vacation.

71
00:08:58,079 --> 00:09:00,457
You try Crema.

72
00:09:00,540 --> 00:09:01,875
Crema?

73
00:09:01,958 --> 00:09:03,460
Thank you.

74
00:09:03,543 --> 00:09:05,086
Is this your orchard?

75
00:09:05,170 --> 00:09:06,588
These are Annella's trees.

76
00:09:07,464 --> 00:09:10,550
Peaches, cherries, apricots...

77
00:09:12,010 --> 00:09:13,386
Pomegranate.

78
00:09:19,142 --> 00:09:20,935
Have another egg.

79
00:09:21,019 --> 00:09:22,437
Oh, stupid.

80
00:09:22,520 --> 00:09:24,314
No, no, no. I know myself too well.

81
00:09:24,397 --> 00:09:25,982
If I have a second,
I'm just gonna have a third,

82
00:09:26,066 --> 00:09:27,901
and then a fourth, and then you're just
gonna have to roll me out of here.

83
00:09:30,070 --> 00:09:31,988
- Delicious.
- Darling?

84
00:09:32,072 --> 00:09:33,490
Thank you.

85
00:09:34,074 --> 00:09:35,992
Shall I give him Anchise's bike?

86
00:10:12,529 --> 00:10:15,115
So, what does one do around here?

87
00:10:15,198 --> 00:10:17,826
Wait for the summer to end.

88
00:10:17,909 --> 00:10:19,327
Yeah?

89
00:10:19,410 --> 00:10:20,620
What do you do in the winter?

90
00:10:20,703 --> 00:10:23,915
- Wait for summer to come?
- Well, we only come here for Christmas

91
00:10:23,998 --> 00:10:25,583
and some other vacations.

92
00:10:25,667 --> 00:10:27,043
- Christmas? I thought you...
- And Easter as well.

93
00:10:27,127 --> 00:10:28,628
- Thought you were Jewish.
- Well, we are Jewish,

94
00:10:28,711 --> 00:10:30,964
but also American, Italian, French.

95
00:10:31,047 --> 00:10:33,299
Somewhat atypical combination.

96
00:10:34,801 --> 00:10:36,261
Besides my family, you're probably

97
00:10:36,344 --> 00:10:38,263
the only other Jew
to set foot in this town.

98
00:10:39,472 --> 00:10:41,224
I'm from a small town in New England.

99
00:10:41,307 --> 00:10:42,475
I know what it's like
to be the odd Jew out.

100
00:10:44,435 --> 00:10:46,396
So, what do you do around here?

101
00:10:47,647 --> 00:10:49,732
Just read books.

102
00:10:49,816 --> 00:10:52,902
Transcribe music. Swim at the river.

103
00:10:52,986 --> 00:10:54,654
- Yeah?
- Go out at night.

104
00:10:54,737 --> 00:10:56,948
- I don't know.
- That sounds fun.

105
00:11:00,702 --> 00:11:02,745
All right, buddy, thanks for the help.

106
00:11:11,838 --> 00:11:13,506
Sorry. Sorry about that.

107
00:11:13,590 --> 00:11:15,049
It's all right.

108
00:11:15,133 --> 00:11:17,135
All right, later.

109
00:11:27,353 --> 00:11:28,771
<i>What do you have there?</i>

110
00:11:28,855 --> 00:11:30,773
That should all be...

111
00:11:34,402 --> 00:11:35,695
What is this?

112
00:11:35,778 --> 00:11:40,283
These are the continuation
of these archaeology department...

113
00:11:40,783 --> 00:11:41,951
These are archaeology?

114
00:11:42,035 --> 00:11:43,745
Yeah, those are archaeology.
The rest of these should be history.

115
00:11:43,828 --> 00:11:44,913
Okay.

116
00:11:44,996 --> 00:11:47,373
- More apricot juice?
- Yeah.

117
00:11:48,208 --> 00:11:49,876
- Here, <i>tesoro.</i>
- Thank you.

118
00:11:49,959 --> 00:11:51,336
Help yourself, darling.

119
00:11:51,419 --> 00:11:52,712
Thanks.

120
00:12:00,845 --> 00:12:02,305
Help yourself to some more.

121
00:12:03,389 --> 00:12:07,477
The word "apricot"
comes from the Arabic.

122
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:11,147
It's like the words "algebra,"
"alchemy," "alcohol."

123
00:12:11,231 --> 00:12:12,815
It derives from an Arabic noun

124
00:12:12,899 --> 00:12:14,817
combined with the Arabic article "al"
before it.

125
00:12:14,901 --> 00:12:18,821
The origin of our Italian <i>albicocca</i>

126
00:12:18,905 --> 00:12:20,531
is <i>al-barquq.</i>

127
00:12:20,615 --> 00:12:23,034
It's amazing that today in Israel
and many Arab countries,

128
00:12:23,117 --> 00:12:26,788
the fruit's referred to
by a totally different name, <i>mismish.</i>

129
00:12:27,372 --> 00:12:29,749
I may have to disagree
with you there, Professor.

130
00:12:31,251 --> 00:12:33,544
I'm gonna talk etymology,
so just bear with me a second.

131
00:12:34,462 --> 00:12:36,005
You're right in the case
that most Latin words

132
00:12:36,089 --> 00:12:38,341
do find their origins in Greek words.

133
00:12:38,424 --> 00:12:39,759
However, in the case of "apricot,"

134
00:12:39,842 --> 00:12:41,636
it's a little bit more
of a complicated journey.

135
00:12:41,719 --> 00:12:43,179
How so?

136
00:12:43,513 --> 00:12:46,224
Well, here, the Greek actually
takes over from the Latin.

137
00:12:46,307 --> 00:12:49,269
Latin word being
<i>praecoquum</i> or <i>precoquere.</i>

138
00:12:49,352 --> 00:12:51,104
So it's, "precook" or "pre-ripen,"
as you know.

139
00:12:51,187 --> 00:12:52,855
To be precocious or premature.

140
00:12:53,606 --> 00:12:57,777
And the Byzantines, to go on,
then borrowed <i>praecox,</i>

141
00:12:57,860 --> 00:13:01,197
which became <i>prekokkia,</i>
which then became <i>berikokki,</i>

142
00:13:01,281 --> 00:13:03,116
which is how the Arabs got <i>al-barquq.</i>

143
00:13:14,085 --> 00:13:15,795
That's courtesy of Philology 101.

144
00:13:16,838 --> 00:13:18,464
Flying colors.

145
00:13:22,218 --> 00:13:23,761
He does this every year.

146
00:13:39,610 --> 00:13:42,071
It's about drink time. Let's go here.

147
00:13:43,239 --> 00:13:45,241
- Ciao, Romano.
- Ciao, Oliver.

148
00:13:45,325 --> 00:13:47,910
- How are you?
- All good.

149
00:13:53,166 --> 00:13:54,709
Ciao, boys!

150
00:13:54,792 --> 00:13:56,627
All good?

151
00:13:56,711 --> 00:13:58,379
All good!

152
00:13:58,463 --> 00:13:59,964
Let's see. What have we got?

153
00:14:00,048 --> 00:14:02,884
- Can you start please?
- Of course!

154
00:14:23,571 --> 00:14:24,822
Good morning, gentlemen.

155
00:14:29,869 --> 00:14:31,871
How do you know about this place?

156
00:14:33,539 --> 00:14:35,041
Okay.

157
00:14:35,291 --> 00:14:36,876
Go, Chiara!

158
00:14:40,963 --> 00:14:41,964
No, no, no, no, no!

159
00:14:45,760 --> 00:14:48,221
He's better than the guy
who came last year.

160
00:14:48,304 --> 00:14:49,680
Remember?

161
00:14:50,181 --> 00:14:51,599
Get in there!

162
00:14:51,682 --> 00:14:54,560
Much better!
See how cute he is.

163
00:15:06,280 --> 00:15:07,782
Elio, water!

164
00:15:09,367 --> 00:15:10,576
Perfect timing.

165
00:15:14,205 --> 00:15:15,665
What's the matter? Are you all right?

166
00:15:16,416 --> 00:15:18,584
- What, pinch a nerve?
- I'm okay.

167
00:15:18,668 --> 00:15:20,545
Here. Hold this.

168
00:15:20,628 --> 00:15:22,630
Trust me. I'm about to be a doctor.

169
00:15:22,713 --> 00:15:24,465
Hey, hey, come here.
See? That's the problem.

170
00:15:24,549 --> 00:15:25,800
You're too stressed.

171
00:15:25,883 --> 00:15:28,344
- You just gotta relax a little bit.
- I am relaxing.

172
00:15:28,428 --> 00:15:30,179
Marzia, come here for a minute.

173
00:15:30,263 --> 00:15:32,640
Back me up here.

174
00:15:33,141 --> 00:15:34,559
- Feel that. Right there?
- Oliver.

175
00:15:34,642 --> 00:15:35,893
- It's too tight, right?
- Yeah.

176
00:15:35,977 --> 00:15:37,186
- He needs to relax.
- Oliver!

177
00:15:37,270 --> 00:15:38,521
Later.

178
00:15:38,604 --> 00:15:40,064
You should relax more.

179
00:15:42,066 --> 00:15:43,484
Okay, guys, ready?

180
00:15:50,908 --> 00:15:52,785
Okay, our ball, our ball, our ball.

181
00:15:52,869 --> 00:15:55,163
Twelve serving 11.

182
00:15:55,246 --> 00:15:57,039
Mine, mine, mine, mine.

183
00:15:57,123 --> 00:15:59,417
Go, go, go. Yeah, good.
It's yours, it's yours.

184
00:16:00,751 --> 00:16:04,380
Sweetheart, Auntie Marcella and
the others are coming over for dinner.

185
00:16:05,173 --> 00:16:07,884
Is Oliver staying with us or going out?

186
00:16:07,967 --> 00:16:09,302
Don't know.

187
00:16:10,219 --> 00:16:11,679
What a movie star!

188
00:16:11,929 --> 00:16:14,474
Yes, those Americans...

189
00:16:37,788 --> 00:16:39,707
Sparkling wine!

190
00:16:40,666 --> 00:16:42,043
He's late.

191
00:16:43,419 --> 00:16:44,712
Don't you think...

192
00:16:45,671 --> 00:16:48,716
Don't you think he's impolite
when he says, "Later"?

193
00:16:49,884 --> 00:16:51,511
Arrogant.

194
00:16:51,594 --> 00:16:53,930
I don't think he's arrogant.

195
00:16:54,013 --> 00:16:55,181
Just watch.

196
00:16:55,264 --> 00:16:57,600
This is how he'll say good-bye
to us when the time comes.

197
00:16:57,683 --> 00:16:59,894
With his... "Later."

198
00:17:01,187 --> 00:17:03,898
Meanwhile, we'll have to put up with him
for six long weeks.

199
00:17:03,981 --> 00:17:06,108
Won't we, darling?

200
00:17:07,068 --> 00:17:08,528
I think he's shy.

201
00:17:08,819 --> 00:17:10,279
You'll grow to like him.

202
00:17:10,363 --> 00:17:11,405
What if I grow to hate him?

203
00:17:11,489 --> 00:17:12,657
Oh, no, sweetheart.

204
00:17:14,867 --> 00:17:17,453
- Take his plates away.
- Very well, madam.

205
00:17:20,915 --> 00:17:22,625
Darling?

206
00:17:42,103 --> 00:17:44,647
Elio, play something.

207
00:17:44,730 --> 00:17:46,440
I don't want to.

208
00:17:47,275 --> 00:17:48,484
Why not?

209
00:17:48,568 --> 00:17:50,027
Because I don't want to.

210
00:17:50,111 --> 00:17:52,446
Why don't you go
to Moscazzano with others?

211
00:17:52,530 --> 00:17:54,240
Because I don't want to.

212
00:17:54,740 --> 00:17:56,450
You're spoiling everyone's fun.

213
00:18:04,959 --> 00:18:06,586
Play well, darling.

214
00:19:39,720 --> 00:19:41,597
- Hey.
- Hey.

215
00:19:41,681 --> 00:19:42,973
What are you doing?

216
00:19:43,057 --> 00:19:44,266
Reading.

217
00:19:46,102 --> 00:19:47,728
How come you're not with everyone else
down by the river?

218
00:19:49,480 --> 00:19:52,274
- I have an allergy. It's...
- Yeah, me too.

219
00:19:52,358 --> 00:19:54,527
Maybe we have the same one.

220
00:19:57,571 --> 00:19:59,073
Why don't you and I go swimming?

221
00:19:59,156 --> 00:20:01,075
- Right now?
- Yeah.

222
00:20:01,158 --> 00:20:03,369
Come on. Let's go.

223
00:20:03,452 --> 00:20:05,705
Do we have to go right now?

224
00:20:07,331 --> 00:20:08,708
- I'll go get changed.
- Okay.

225
00:20:08,791 --> 00:20:10,251
Meet you downstairs.

226
00:20:29,228 --> 00:20:30,438
See you downstairs.

227
00:21:05,264 --> 00:21:07,850
Elio, what are you doing?

228
00:21:07,933 --> 00:21:09,518
Reading my music.

229
00:21:09,602 --> 00:21:11,979
No, you're not.

230
00:21:12,062 --> 00:21:14,231
- Thinking, then.
- Yeah?

231
00:21:17,401 --> 00:21:18,736
About what?

232
00:21:21,363 --> 00:21:22,782
It's private.

233
00:21:23,365 --> 00:21:24,617
You're not gonna tell me?

234
00:21:24,700 --> 00:21:26,452
I'm not gonna tell you.

235
00:21:26,535 --> 00:21:28,454
He's not gonna tell me
what he's thinking about.

236
00:21:28,537 --> 00:21:29,622
Elio.

237
00:21:29,705 --> 00:21:31,373
I guess I'll go hang out with your mom.

238
00:21:32,541 --> 00:21:34,543
More apricot juice, please.

239
00:21:35,878 --> 00:21:37,630
That's a good boy.

240
00:21:37,713 --> 00:21:39,256
Thank God you're helping me.

241
00:22:01,445 --> 00:22:03,364
Sounds nice.

242
00:22:04,031 --> 00:22:05,658
Thought you didn't like it.

243
00:22:11,580 --> 00:22:13,040
Play it again, will you?

244
00:22:22,716 --> 00:22:24,385
Follow me.

245
00:22:56,667 --> 00:22:58,711
That sounds different.
Did you change it?

246
00:22:58,794 --> 00:23:01,463
- Well, I changed it a little bit.
- Why?

247
00:23:01,547 --> 00:23:03,632
I just played it the way Liszt
would have played it

248
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:06,010
if he'd altered Bach's version.

249
00:23:06,093 --> 00:23:08,012
Play that again.

250
00:23:08,095 --> 00:23:10,097
- Play what again?
- The thing you played outside.

251
00:23:10,180 --> 00:23:12,474
You want me to play
the thing I played outside?

252
00:23:12,558 --> 00:23:15,519
- Please.
- Of course.

253
00:23:39,084 --> 00:23:40,628
I can't believe you changed it again.

254
00:23:40,711 --> 00:23:43,255
- I changed it a little bit.
- Yeah. Why?

255
00:23:43,339 --> 00:23:45,716
I just played it the way
Busoni would've played it

256
00:23:45,799 --> 00:23:47,301
if he'd altered Liszt's version.

257
00:23:47,384 --> 00:23:49,303
And what is wrong with Bach
the way Bach would've played...

258
00:23:49,386 --> 00:23:50,930
Bach never wrote it for the guitar.

259
00:23:51,013 --> 00:23:52,348
In fact, we're not even sure

260
00:23:52,431 --> 00:23:54,308
- Bach wrote it at all.
- Forget I asked.

261
00:24:24,672 --> 00:24:26,465
It's young Bach.

262
00:24:26,548 --> 00:24:28,425
He dedicated it to his brother.

263
00:25:02,084 --> 00:25:03,711
Hey, Professor.

264
00:25:03,794 --> 00:25:04,920
Hello.

265
00:25:05,004 --> 00:25:07,131
Here, please.

266
00:25:07,214 --> 00:25:08,799
I need help.

267
00:25:10,801 --> 00:25:12,302
Just be honest.

268
00:25:12,386 --> 00:25:13,595
How bad is it?

269
00:25:13,679 --> 00:25:17,266
I think your insights here
are persuasive, but...

270
00:25:20,811 --> 00:25:22,771
Have you been to the river?

271
00:25:37,119 --> 00:25:38,454
Mafalda!

272
00:25:39,038 --> 00:25:40,372
Isn't she beautiful?

273
00:26:00,017 --> 00:26:01,268
Elio.

274
00:26:02,478 --> 00:26:03,979
You sleeping?

275
00:26:05,439 --> 00:26:06,774
I was.

276
00:26:06,857 --> 00:26:09,526
Listen to this drivel.
Tell me what you think.

277
00:26:10,402 --> 00:26:12,821
- Wait.
- What?

278
00:26:12,905 --> 00:26:14,615
Can't hear you.

279
00:26:23,707 --> 00:26:25,542
"For the early Greeks,

280
00:26:25,626 --> 00:26:27,252
"Heidegger contends,
this underlying hiddenness

281
00:26:27,336 --> 00:26:29,129
"is constitutive of the way beings are,

282
00:26:29,213 --> 00:26:30,547
"not only in relation to themselves

283
00:26:30,631 --> 00:26:33,258
"but also in relation
to other entities generally.

284
00:26:33,342 --> 00:26:35,052
"In other words,
they do not construe hiddenness

285
00:26:35,135 --> 00:26:38,639
"merely or primarily in terms of
entities' relations to human beings."

286
00:26:40,015 --> 00:26:42,059
Does that make any sense to you?

287
00:26:42,142 --> 00:26:44,520
Doesn't make any sense to me.

288
00:26:44,603 --> 00:26:46,563
I don't think it makes
any sense to your dad, either.

289
00:26:47,898 --> 00:26:49,608
Maybe it did when you wrote it.

290
00:26:54,571 --> 00:26:57,407
That might be the kindest thing
anybody has said to me in months.

291
00:26:58,117 --> 00:27:00,119
"Kind"?

292
00:27:00,202 --> 00:27:02,204
Yep. Kind.

293
00:27:27,855 --> 00:27:31,066
- Hey, Elio.
- Hey.

294
00:27:31,150 --> 00:27:32,526
Hey!

295
00:27:35,362 --> 00:27:36,530
Come here.

296
00:27:38,866 --> 00:27:40,284
What's going on?

297
00:27:40,367 --> 00:27:42,161
Is he trying to get it on with her?

298
00:27:42,286 --> 00:27:44,413
Elio, he already succeeded?

299
00:27:46,331 --> 00:27:47,749
What do I know?

300
00:27:47,833 --> 00:27:49,501
I'd love to be in his shoes.

301
00:27:49,585 --> 00:27:51,503
Who wouldn't love to be in her shoes?

302
00:27:53,964 --> 00:27:56,216
She wants him, no matter what!

303
00:28:40,469 --> 00:28:41,637
Coming?

304
00:28:43,972 --> 00:28:45,307
I'll come later.

305
00:30:00,716 --> 00:30:03,593
Are you with me because
you're mad at Chiara?

306
00:30:03,677 --> 00:30:05,345
Why would I be mad at Chiara?

307
00:30:06,555 --> 00:30:08,056
Because of him.

308
00:30:08,140 --> 00:30:09,599
Because of who?

309
00:30:10,767 --> 00:30:12,019
Of Oliver.

310
00:30:23,530 --> 00:30:24,906
Turn around.

311
00:30:39,546 --> 00:30:41,381
Meet me here tomorrow night?

312
00:30:48,263 --> 00:30:50,557
Wait for me!

313
00:30:50,640 --> 00:30:52,184
Come on.

314
00:31:05,614 --> 00:31:07,616
We almost had sex last night...

315
00:31:07,699 --> 00:31:10,077
Marzia and me.

316
00:31:11,870 --> 00:31:13,580
Well, why didn't you?

317
00:31:14,373 --> 00:31:15,874
I don't know.

318
00:31:17,000 --> 00:31:19,711
Well, you know, it's better
to have tried and failed, right?

319
00:31:19,795 --> 00:31:23,590
All I had to do was find the courage
to reach out and touch.

320
00:31:23,673 --> 00:31:25,217
She would have said yes.

321
00:31:25,300 --> 00:31:27,094
Well, try again later.

322
00:31:27,177 --> 00:31:28,929
Try what later?

323
00:31:29,012 --> 00:31:30,680
I just heard
from the people in Sirmione.

324
00:31:30,764 --> 00:31:32,599
They say they've come up with something.

325
00:31:32,682 --> 00:31:34,976
Fantastic.

326
00:31:35,060 --> 00:31:36,603
Going there today.

327
00:31:36,686 --> 00:31:39,022
- Would you like to come along?
- I would love to. Thank you.

328
00:31:40,565 --> 00:31:42,609
- Smell this.
- Can I come, too?

329
00:31:42,692 --> 00:31:45,278
On the condition you remain silent.

330
00:31:45,904 --> 00:31:47,197
Silent as in,
"He has too many opinions,"

331
00:31:47,280 --> 00:31:48,865
or silent as in,
"Just not telling anybody

332
00:31:48,949 --> 00:31:50,617
"what an amazing thing you've dug up"?

333
00:31:50,700 --> 00:31:52,244
Well, nothing has been dug up.

334
00:31:52,327 --> 00:31:54,955
It's what has been brought out,
out of the water.

335
00:32:03,713 --> 00:32:05,215
What are you doing?

336
00:32:05,298 --> 00:32:07,217
Going to Lake Garda with my dad.

337
00:32:07,300 --> 00:32:09,302
He wants to show Oliver
where he's dredging.

338
00:32:10,262 --> 00:32:11,638
Can you tell him I came by?

339
00:32:12,597 --> 00:32:14,474
He's inside with my dad, helping him.

340
00:32:16,309 --> 00:32:19,729
You were amazing last night,
on the dance floor.

341
00:32:19,813 --> 00:32:21,690
- He's a good dancer.
- A good dancer.

342
00:32:24,067 --> 00:32:25,735
He's good-looking too.

343
00:32:27,195 --> 00:32:28,989
- Want to get us together?
- No.

344
00:32:30,740 --> 00:32:32,409
Come in.

345
00:33:09,154 --> 00:33:11,698
Dad always sits up front
with Anchise to navigate.

346
00:33:19,289 --> 00:33:21,750
She seems to like you a lot.

347
00:33:21,833 --> 00:33:24,503
She's more beautiful
than she was last year.

348
00:33:25,921 --> 00:33:29,382
I saw her naked on a night swim once.

349
00:33:29,466 --> 00:33:31,426
Great body.

350
00:33:31,593 --> 00:33:33,220
Trying to get me to like her?

351
00:33:33,303 --> 00:33:35,388
What would be the harm in that?

352
00:33:35,472 --> 00:33:36,640
No, no harm.

353
00:33:36,723 --> 00:33:38,767
Just typically like to go at those
things on my own, if you don't mind.

354
00:33:43,688 --> 00:33:44,940
I'll drive today!

355
00:33:49,319 --> 00:33:51,321
Just don't play at being the good host.

356
00:33:53,198 --> 00:33:56,618
Anchise, take the afternoon off.

357
00:33:58,912 --> 00:34:00,455
What's going on, boys?

358
00:34:01,706 --> 00:34:07,087
Oliver, come. Sit up front.
Be my navigator.

359
00:34:07,170 --> 00:34:09,631
What? What?

360
00:34:24,688 --> 00:34:26,856
-Dr Roseburg.
-Samuel!

361
00:34:26,940 --> 00:34:28,900
<i>- Benvenuto.</i>
- Look who's here.

362
00:34:30,485 --> 00:34:32,237
- He's grown a bit, eh?
- And this is Oliver.

363
00:35:01,766 --> 00:35:03,518
Sammy! Come on!

364
00:35:16,573 --> 00:35:18,033
Truce?

365
00:35:19,659 --> 00:35:21,328
Hey, boys.

366
00:35:27,042 --> 00:35:32,297
The ship went down in 1827
on the way to Isola del Garda

367
00:35:32,380 --> 00:35:36,509
Gossip has it this statue
was a gift from Count Lechi

368
00:35:36,593 --> 00:35:39,763
to his lover,
contralto Adelaide Malanotte.

369
00:35:42,182 --> 00:35:46,561
There are four known sets,
after the Praxiteles originals.

370
00:35:46,645 --> 00:35:48,188
This fellow's at number three.

371
00:35:48,271 --> 00:35:50,857
The Emperor Hadrian had a pair,
dug up at Tivoli,

372
00:35:50,940 --> 00:35:54,861
but one of the more philistine
of the Farnese Popes melted them down

373
00:35:54,944 --> 00:35:58,782
and had them recast as a
particularly voluptuous Venus.

374
00:36:19,344 --> 00:36:22,681
Who'd like to go for a swim
before we head back?

375
00:36:22,764 --> 00:36:28,061
We're all such pros. If I got my own
statue, it would probably be on there.

376
00:36:34,943 --> 00:36:36,569
Elio!

377
00:36:36,653 --> 00:36:38,613
Oliver!

378
00:36:42,033 --> 00:36:43,952
- I have to go. I have to go.
- Hey! Hey!

379
00:36:44,035 --> 00:36:45,745
I have to go.

380
00:36:47,539 --> 00:36:49,082
Goodness.

381
00:36:52,877 --> 00:36:55,171
- Are you going, too?
- No, no.

382
00:36:55,255 --> 00:36:57,340
I should stay
and do some work on my book.

383
00:36:57,424 --> 00:37:00,009
Come on. How about a drink
to celebrate the day?

384
00:37:00,802 --> 00:37:03,304
- Okay, maybe just one.
- All right!

385
00:37:14,566 --> 00:37:16,025
Marzia?

386
00:38:20,673 --> 00:38:23,635
<i>The Cosmic Fragments</i> by Heraclitus.

387
00:38:31,851 --> 00:38:35,104
<i>The meaning of the river flowing
is not that all things are changing</i>

388
00:38:35,188 --> 00:38:37,190
<i>so that we cannot encounter them twice,</i>

389
00:38:37,273 --> 00:38:40,401
<i>but that some things
stay the same only by changing.</i>

390
00:39:28,283 --> 00:39:31,035
Sorry, Elio.
I brought some clean clothes.

391
00:39:36,124 --> 00:39:37,584
Leave the door open.

392
00:39:38,710 --> 00:39:40,378
- Thanks.
- You're welcome.

393
00:42:29,172 --> 00:42:31,090
Darling, have you seen my <i>Heptaméron?</i>

394
00:42:34,218 --> 00:42:35,344
Mafalda.

395
00:42:40,183 --> 00:42:41,642
It's in German.

396
00:42:43,853 --> 00:42:44,896
Okay.

397
00:42:47,648 --> 00:42:51,444
I can't remember where we left off,
but I think you'll like this one.

398
00:42:54,697 --> 00:42:56,616
Come here, darling.

399
00:42:58,576 --> 00:43:00,369
So, I'll translate, huh?

400
00:43:09,629 --> 00:43:13,800
"A handsome young knight
is madly in love with a princess.

401
00:43:13,966 --> 00:43:15,885
"And she, too, is in love with him,

402
00:43:17,220 --> 00:43:20,598
"though she seems not to be
entirely aware of it.

403
00:43:21,641 --> 00:43:23,392
"Despite the friendship..."

404
00:43:25,853 --> 00:43:28,981
"...that blossoms between them,

405
00:43:30,024 --> 00:43:32,902
"or perhaps because of
that very friendship,

406
00:43:34,112 --> 00:43:36,489
"the young knight finds himself so..."

407
00:43:39,700 --> 00:43:41,994
"...so humbled and speechless

408
00:43:42,954 --> 00:43:47,083
"that he's totally unable to bring up
the subject of his love.

409
00:43:47,959 --> 00:43:51,671
"Till one day, he asks the princess
point-blank..."

410
00:44:03,015 --> 00:44:05,184
"Is it better to speak or to die?"

411
00:44:10,565 --> 00:44:13,609
I'd never have the courage
to ask a question like that.

412
00:44:15,194 --> 00:44:16,445
I doubt that.

413
00:44:21,200 --> 00:44:23,578
Hey, Elly-Belly.

414
00:44:25,371 --> 00:44:27,540
You do know that
you can always talk to us.

415
00:44:34,213 --> 00:44:37,341
My mom's been reading
this 16th-century French romance.

416
00:44:37,425 --> 00:44:39,677
She read some of it to my dad and I
the day the lights went out.

417
00:44:40,553 --> 00:44:43,139
Yeah, about the knight that doesn't know
whether to speak or die?

418
00:44:43,222 --> 00:44:44,307
Right.

419
00:44:45,558 --> 00:44:46,976
So, does he or doesn't he?

420
00:44:48,978 --> 00:44:50,771
"Better to speak," she said.

421
00:44:52,732 --> 00:44:54,483
But she's on her guard.

422
00:44:55,860 --> 00:44:57,778
She senses a trap somewhere.

423
00:45:04,744 --> 00:45:06,037
So, does he speak?

424
00:45:07,288 --> 00:45:08,372
No.

425
00:45:10,666 --> 00:45:11,792
He fudges.

426
00:45:13,878 --> 00:45:16,255
It figures. He's French.

427
00:45:22,511 --> 00:45:24,889
I gotta go to town in a little bit
to pick some things up.

428
00:45:24,972 --> 00:45:28,434
I can go. I'm not doing anything today.

429
00:45:29,727 --> 00:45:31,187
Then why don't we go together?

430
00:45:31,270 --> 00:45:32,438
Right now?

431
00:45:32,521 --> 00:45:34,732
Yeah. Right now.

432
00:45:35,775 --> 00:45:38,194
That is, of course, unless you have
more important business going on.

433
00:45:38,277 --> 00:45:40,613
"That is, of course, unless you have
more important business going on."

434
00:45:52,959 --> 00:45:53,960
Mind if I put this in your bag?

435
00:45:54,043 --> 00:45:55,044
Yes, please.

436
00:46:06,138 --> 00:46:08,140
I straightened the wheels
and inflated the tires.

437
00:46:08,224 --> 00:46:09,642
Perfect. Thanks.

438
00:46:11,811 --> 00:46:16,190
I fell. I was coming home the other day,
and I scraped myself pretty badly.

439
00:46:16,482 --> 00:46:19,068
Anchiese insisted on applying
some sort of witches' brew.

440
00:46:19,277 --> 00:46:20,695
I think it helped.

441
00:46:45,052 --> 00:46:46,429
Hold this for a second, will you?

442
00:47:06,324 --> 00:47:07,658
- Want one?
- Sure.

443
00:47:32,516 --> 00:47:33,601
Not bad, huh?

444
00:47:34,393 --> 00:47:35,519
Not bad at all.

445
00:47:38,564 --> 00:47:39,857
I thought you didn't smoke.

446
00:47:41,484 --> 00:47:42,568
I don't.

447
00:47:48,199 --> 00:47:51,202
- So, World War II, huh?
- No. This is World War I.

448
00:47:51,994 --> 00:47:54,455
You'd have to be at least 80 years old
to have known any of them.

449
00:47:55,581 --> 00:47:57,666
I never even heard
of the Battle of Piave.

450
00:47:57,792 --> 00:48:00,419
Battle of Piave was one of the most
lethal battles of World War I.

451
00:48:01,087 --> 00:48:02,797
Hundred and seventy thousand
people died.

452
00:48:04,340 --> 00:48:06,175
Is there anything you don't know?

453
00:48:10,137 --> 00:48:11,597
I know nothing, Oliver.

454
00:48:16,685 --> 00:48:18,354
Well, you seem to know
more than anybody else around here.

455
00:48:18,437 --> 00:48:20,898
Well, if you only knew how little
I know about the things that matter.

456
00:48:24,110 --> 00:48:25,486
What things that matter?

457
00:48:32,827 --> 00:48:33,953
You know what things.

458
00:48:41,168 --> 00:48:42,503
Why are you telling me this?

459
00:48:46,966 --> 00:48:48,134
'Cause I thought you should know.

460
00:48:50,094 --> 00:48:51,887
Because you thought I should know?

461
00:48:54,682 --> 00:48:56,016
'Cause I wanted you to know?

462
00:48:59,603 --> 00:49:01,564
Because I wanted you to know.

463
00:49:05,609 --> 00:49:07,278
Because I wanted you to know.

464
00:49:12,158 --> 00:49:14,493
'Cause I wanted you to know.

465
00:49:25,421 --> 00:49:28,257
Because there's no one else
I can say this to but you.

466
00:49:35,014 --> 00:49:36,765
Are you saying
what I think you're saying?

467
00:49:44,148 --> 00:49:46,442
Don't go anywhere. Stay right here.

468
00:49:47,860 --> 00:49:49,528
You know I'm not going anywhere.

469
00:50:18,974 --> 00:50:20,518
They mixed up all of my pages.

470
00:50:20,601 --> 00:50:22,728
I'm gonna have to
retype this whole thing.

471
00:50:23,229 --> 00:50:24,605
I'm not gonna have anything to work on
this afternoon.

472
00:50:24,688 --> 00:50:26,232
This is gonna set me back a whole day.

473
00:50:27,066 --> 00:50:28,108
Damn it.

474
00:50:29,401 --> 00:50:31,320
Shouldn't have said anything.

475
00:50:31,612 --> 00:50:32,780
Just pretend you never did.

476
00:50:32,863 --> 00:50:35,115
Does that mean we're on speaking terms
but not really?

477
00:50:38,619 --> 00:50:40,955
It means we can't talk
about those kinds of things.

478
00:50:42,081 --> 00:50:43,332
Okay?

479
00:50:45,084 --> 00:50:46,293
We just can't.

480
00:51:01,392 --> 00:51:02,601
Hey.

481
00:51:03,477 --> 00:51:05,354
Let's go, American!

482
00:51:26,333 --> 00:51:28,085
- Ready?
- Let's go.

483
00:52:03,746 --> 00:52:04,872
Pretty much.

484
00:52:13,172 --> 00:52:14,673
Oh, my God.

485
00:52:15,132 --> 00:52:16,800
- Thirsty?
- Yeah.

486
00:52:19,094 --> 00:52:20,679
Good morning, ma'am.

487
00:52:22,264 --> 00:52:23,557
Excuse me.

488
00:52:24,475 --> 00:52:27,186
Could I ask for a glass of water?

489
00:52:37,905 --> 00:52:39,198
Il Duce.

490
00:52:39,281 --> 00:52:41,075
"People of Italy!"

491
00:52:42,326 --> 00:52:43,577
That's Italy.

492
00:52:47,539 --> 00:52:49,083
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

493
00:53:27,913 --> 00:53:28,914
Come on!

494
00:53:50,936 --> 00:53:53,355
This is my spot. It's all mine.

495
00:53:55,357 --> 00:53:56,692
Come here to read.

496
00:53:58,152 --> 00:54:00,112
Can't tell you the number of books
I've read here.

497
00:54:02,823 --> 00:54:05,200
Oh, my God, it's freezing.

498
00:54:06,160 --> 00:54:07,786
Spring is in the mountains.

499
00:54:08,620 --> 00:54:10,038
The Alpi Orobie.

500
00:54:11,373 --> 00:54:12,750
The water comes
straight down from there.

501
00:54:39,067 --> 00:54:40,944
I like the way you say things.

502
00:54:41,028 --> 00:54:43,197
I don't know why you're always
putting yourself down, though.

503
00:54:43,655 --> 00:54:45,657
So you won't, I guess.

504
00:54:49,995 --> 00:54:51,997
You really that afraid of what I think?

505
00:55:04,927 --> 00:55:06,470
You're making things
very difficult for me.

506
00:55:19,608 --> 00:55:21,151
I love this, Oliver.

507
00:55:27,032 --> 00:55:28,033
What?

508
00:55:32,371 --> 00:55:33,497
Everything.

509
00:55:38,544 --> 00:55:39,920
Us, you mean?

510
00:55:41,797 --> 00:55:43,048
It's not bad.

511
00:55:44,132 --> 00:55:45,175
It's not bad.

512
00:56:40,147 --> 00:56:41,231
Better now?

513
00:56:49,823 --> 00:56:51,867
No, no, no.

514
00:56:52,951 --> 00:56:54,578
- We should go.
- Why?

515
00:56:55,120 --> 00:56:57,956
I know myself. Okay?
And we've been good.

516
00:56:58,040 --> 00:56:59,291
We haven't done anything
to be ashamed of,

517
00:56:59,374 --> 00:57:00,667
and that's a good thing.

518
00:57:01,293 --> 00:57:02,461
I wanna be good.

519
00:57:03,211 --> 00:57:04,212
Okay?

520
00:57:11,136 --> 00:57:12,846
Am I offending you?

521
00:57:19,728 --> 00:57:20,896
Just don't.

522
00:57:28,028 --> 00:57:30,197
I think it's starting to get infected.

